{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013k92b4XrWaApWXfhniZV1z","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 28 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→All 11 failures are on generated files. No real-file failures this iteration.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter corruption in first-line title (5 failures)\n     8→\n     9→**Files:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Żurek Krakowski\n    10→\n    11→The title appears as the very first line but contains OCR substitutions (e.g. `1` for `i`/`l`, `¡` for `i`). Line 2 is always a parenthetical corruption note, and line 5 is `lngredients:` (itself corrupted).\n    12→\n    13→**What was extracted vs expected:**\n    14→- Braised Cod, Roasted Beet → extracted nothing (empty)\n    15→- Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami → extracted a closing serving suggestion from the body\n    16→- Żurek Krakowski → extracted garbage tokens (`XxYyZz salt and pepper`)\n    17→\n    18→**Why:** The extractor apparently rejects the first line when it contains digit-substitution corruption, then falls through to pick an arbitrary body line. The inconsistency (empty vs wrong line) suggests the fallback logic is non-deterministic or position-based rather than semantic.\n    19→\n    20→**Fix direction:** Apply fuzzy/normalized matching on the first line — strip digits that look like letters (1→i, 0→o) before confidence scoring, or explicitly prefer the first non-empty line even when OCR confidence is low.\n    21→\n    22→---\n    23→\n    24→## Pattern 2: Section/category header precedes the real title (3 failures)\n    25→\n    26→**Files:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Ogórkowa Zupa\n    27→\n    28→The true title is not on line 1. Instead:\n    29→- Halibut / Roasted Asparagus: Line 1 is an ALL-CAPS category header (`FISH & SEAFOOD`, `VEGETABLES`), line 3 is the recipe title.\n    30→- Ogórkowa Zupa: Line 1 is a pipe-separated metadata string (`Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | PRZYGOTOWANIE 15 MIN | GOTOWANIE 20 MIN`), line 3 is the ALL-CAPS title `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA`.\n    31→\n    32→**What was extracted vs expected:**\n    33→- Halibut → extracted a mid-document instruction line\n    34→- Roasted Asparagus → extracted the subtitle/description line immediately after the title\n    35→- Ogórkowa Zupa → extracted nothing (empty)\n    36→\n    37→**Why:** The extractor treats line 1 as the title candidate. When line 1 is rejected (it's a category header or metadata), the fallback doesn't correctly skip to the next title-like line. For Roasted Asparagus, the description line was promoted because it immediately follows the title and may score higher. For Ogórkowa Zupa, the ALL-CAPS title on line 3 wasn't recognized (possibly filtered as noise or confused with a header).\n    38→\n    39→**Fix direction:** Add a skip-list for common non-title first-line patterns: ALL-CAPS single-category words, pipe-delimited metadata strings. After skipping, treat the next short standalone line as the title candidate. ALL-CAPS multi-word lines that look like recipe names should be accepted, not filtered.\n    40→\n    41→---\n    42→\n    43→## Pattern 3: Title absent from the document beginning (2 failures)\n    44→\n    45→**Files:** Mushroom Risotto, Peach Cobbler\n    46→\n    47→The file begins mid-recipe — either a continuation from a previous page or a section break — so the actual recipe title never appears near the top.\n    48→\n    49→**What was extracted vs expected:**\n    50→- Mushroom Risotto → extracted `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` (a different recipe title appearing later in the same document)\n    51→- Peach Cobbler → extracted `Assembly: 1. Preheat oven to 375°F (I90°C)` (an instruction line)\n    52→\n    53→**Why:** When the true title isn't present at the start, the extractor latches onto the first prominent-looking string it finds anywhere in the document. For Mushroom Risotto, that happened to be another recipe's ALL-CAPS title. For Peach Cobbler, it found an instruction with a capital word.\n    54→\n    55→**Fix direction:** These are inherently ambiguous inputs. A reasonable heuristic: if the first 3 lines contain `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE]` or similar continuation markers, signal low confidence and return empty rather than a wrong answer. For the Mushroom Risotto case (no corruption marker), the challenge is harder — the extractor needs to know that a title mid-document doesn't belong to this recipe.\n    56→\n    57→---\n    58→\n    59→## Pattern 4: Mixed-case OCR corruption in title (1 failure)\n    60→\n    61→**File:** Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi\n    62→\n    63→The title on line 1 is `KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi` — erratic capitalization plus a dotless `¡` substitution for `i`.\n    64→\n    65→**What was extracted vs expected:**\n    66→- Extracted: `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` (a cooking step)\n    67→- Expected: `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi`\n    68→\n    69→**Why:** The random capitalization pattern may cause the extractor to score line 1 as non-title (it doesn't match a typical title-case or ALL-CAPS pattern). It then falls through to a body line.\n    70→\n    71→**Fix direction:** Normalize candidate lines to title-case before pattern-matching. Erratic casing on an otherwise short, non-punctuated first line should still be treated as a title candidate.\n    72→\n    73→---\n    74→\n    75→## Summary table\n    76→\n    77→| Pattern | Count | Extractor behavior | Affects real files? |\n    78→|---|---|---|---|\n    79→| OCR digit substitution in first-line title | 5 | Empty or random body line | Not observed yet |\n    80→| Category header / metadata before title | 3 | Wrong line or empty | Likely (cookbooks with headers) |\n    81→| Title absent from document start | 2 | Different recipe name or instruction | Likely (multi-page scans) |\n    82→| Mixed-case OCR corruption | 1 | Body line | Possible |\n    83→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01QxrA3xJSbnshGa1Pt2TJYu","session_id":"c37a3300-1904-44e6-bf34-65ba8b38fada","uuid":"6cd4efa8-a88c-4370-b27f-aee96151569c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LqFU2k4bqWJXTd1rnXJfh8","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 27 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→All 11 failures are generated files. No real file failures.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter corruption on title line (5 cases)\n     8→\n     9→**Affected:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip, Żurek Krakowski\n    10→\n    11→The title appears on line 1 but contains OCR corruption (e.g. `Bra1sed`, `Sern1k`, `D1p`, `P1ern1k`). The extractor either:\n    12→- Returns empty (Braised Cod, Roasted Beet) — likely rejected the corrupted line as non-title\n    13→- Returns a later line (Drożdże → `Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.`, Piernik → `Podaw4ć ciepło ze śmietaną lub lodami.`, Żurek → `XxYyZz salt and pepper`) — picked garbage/instruction text instead\n    14→\n    15→**Root cause:** The extractor penalizes or skips lines with digit-for-letter substitutions. When it rejects the (corrupted) title line, it either falls back to nothing or picks the next \"prominent-looking\" line, which may be garbage text injected into the OCR stream.\n    16→\n    17→**Fix direction:** The extractor should tolerate mild digit-for-letter corruption (1→i/l, 4→a, etc.) on an otherwise title-shaped line, especially when it appears first.\n    18→\n    19→---\n    20→\n    21→## Pattern 2: Category/section header precedes the title (3 cases)\n    22→\n    23→**Affected:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Ogórkowa Zupa\n    24→\n    25→The real title is on line 2 or 3, preceded by a section header (`FISH & SEAFOOD`, `VEGETABLES`) or a metadata line (`Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | PRZYGOTOWANIE 15 MIN | ...`). The extractor:\n    26→- Skips past the header correctly but then picks the subtitle/description instead of the title (Halibut → instruction body; Roasted Asparagus → description sentence)\n    27→- Returns empty (Ogórkowa Zupa) — the metadata line may have confused position logic\n    28→\n    29→**Root cause:** After skipping a section header, the extractor doesn't reliably land on the next line as the title. For the pipe-separated metadata case, it may not recognise the pattern as \"skip this\" at all.\n    30→\n    31→**Fix direction:** After identifying and skipping a section header or metadata line, the immediately following line should be treated as the title candidate. Pipe-separated metadata lines (`word | word | ...`) should be recognized as non-title and skipped.\n    32→\n    33→---\n    34→\n    35→## Pattern 3: Multi-line split title (1 case)\n    36→\n    37→**Affected:** Lemon Herb Roasted Vegetables\n    38→\n    39→The title is split across two lines due to page layout: `LEMON HERB RO45TED` / `VEGETABLES`. The extractor returned only the first fragment (`LEMON HERB ROASTED`), missing the continuation.\n    40→\n    41→**Root cause:** The extractor treats each line independently and stops at the first \"title-shaped\" line. It doesn't check whether the following line could be a title continuation (short, all-caps, no verb/punctuation).\n    42→\n    43→**Fix direction:** If a candidate title line is short and the next line is also short and all-caps (or title-cased) with no sentence-ending punctuation, concatenate them as a single title.\n    44→\n    45→---\n    46→\n    47→## Pattern 4: Previous-page content before the title (2 cases)\n    48→\n    49→**Affected:** Mushroom Risotto, Peach Cobbler\n    50→\n    51→The file starts with content from the end of a previous recipe (cooking instructions, ingredient continuations). The actual recipe title (`Mushroom Risotto`, `Peach Cobbler`) is buried later in the file. The extractor returned:\n    52→- `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` (a different recipe's title that appeared mid-file)\n    53→- `Assembly: 1. Preheat oven to 375°F (I90°C)` (an instruction line)\n    54→\n    55→**Root cause:** When the beginning of the file is clearly mid-recipe content, the extractor should scan forward. But it either picks the first all-caps/bold-looking line it finds (which is a different recipe's title in the Mushroom Risotto case) or a random instruction line.\n    56→\n    57→**Fix direction:** Presence of a `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE]` marker or mid-instruction opening lines should trigger a forward scan for the first standalone title-shaped line, ignoring embedded titles from adjacent recipes.\n    58→\n    59→---\n    60→\n    61→## Summary table\n    62→\n    63→| Pattern | Count | Real files | Generated files |\n    64→|---|---|---|---|\n    65→| OCR digit-for-letter on title line | 5 | 0 | 5 |\n    66→| Category header / metadata before title | 3 | 0 | 3 |\n    67→| Multi-line split title | 1 | 0 | 1 |\n    68→| Previous-page content before title | 2 | 0 | 2 |\n    69→| **Total** | **11** | **0** | **11** |\n    70→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01QxrA3xJSbnshGa1Pt2TJYu","session_id":"c37a3300-1904-44e6-bf34-65ba8b38fada","uuid":"92b12ef1-62b9-4a14-9d5b-c14778129f21"}
