{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MmNACa9REeadLJL9hmAk5y","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Task 01: Extract `applyBlindOcrRepair` and add OCR-repaired variants for early candidates\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Extract blind digit→letter substitution logic from `normalizeOcrTitle` into a reusable `applyBlindOcrRepair` function, then call it in `buildCandidates` to generate OCR-repaired variant candidates for the first few lines.\n     6→\n     7→## Files to modify\n     8→\n     9→- `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n    10→\n    11→## Changes\n    12→\n    13→### 1. Add `applyBlindOcrRepair` function (after `repairOcrText` ~line 810)\n    14→\n    15→Extract the blind substitution logic from `normalizeOcrTitle` (lines 832-863) into a standalone function. This function applies the same digit→letter substitutions but as a candidate generator (before embedding), not post-processing (after winner selection).\n    16→\n    17→```typescript\n    18→/**\n    19→ * Apply blind OCR digit-for-letter repair without dictionary lookup.\n    20→ * Used to generate additional candidates for early-position lines where\n    21→ * positional evidence is strong enough to justify speculative repair.\n    22→ */\n    23→function applyBlindOcrRepair(text: string): string {\n    24→  if (isAllCaps(text)) {\n    25→    return text\n    26→      .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n    27→      .replace(/0(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"O\")\n    28→      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0/g, \"O\")\n    29→      .replace(/4(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"A\")\n    30→      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, \"A\")\n    31→      .replace(/5(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"S\")\n    32→      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])5/g, \"S\")\n    33→      .replace(/¡/g, \"I\")\n    34→      .replace(/€/g, \"E\")\n    35→      .replace(/[ÍÌ]/g, \"I\");\n    36→  }\n    37→  // Mixed-case: fix per-word (digits between lowercase letters)\n    38→  return text.split(/(\\s+)/).map((token) => {\n    39→    if (/^\\s+$/.test(token)) return token;\n    40→    if (isAllCaps(token) && token.length > 1) {\n    41→      return token\n    42→        .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n    43→        .replace(/0(?=[A-Z])/g, \"O\")\n    44→        .replace(/(?<=[A-Z])0/g, \"O\");\n    45→    }\n    46→    return token\n    47→      .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, \"l\")\n    48→      .replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"l\")\n    49→      .replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n    50→      .replace(/€/g, \"e\");\n    51→  }).join(\"\");\n    52→}\n    53→```\n    54→\n    55→### 2. Refactor `normalizeOcrTitle` to use `applyBlindOcrRepair`\n    56→\n    57→Replace the inline substitution logic in `normalizeOcrTitle` (lines 832-863) with a call to the new function:\n    58→\n    59→```typescript\n    60→// Step 2: OCR character substitution.\n    61→const beforeSub = text;\n    62→text = applyBlindOcrRepair(text);\n    63→```\n    64→\n    65→This is a pure refactor — no behavioral change.\n    66→\n    67→### 3. Add blind-repaired variant candidates in `buildCandidates`\n    68→\n    69→In the `buildCandidates` function, after the single-line candidate is added (around line 653-655), add a block that generates a blind-repaired variant for early-position candidates:\n    70→\n    71→```typescript\n    72→    // Single line candidate added above...\n    73→    candidates.push({ text: singleText, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n    74→      }\n    75→    }\n    76→\n    77→    // Blind OCR repair for early-position candidates: when the original text\n    78→    // has OCR artifacts and is in the first few lines (strong positional evidence),\n    79→    // generate an additional candidate with blind digit→letter repair.\n    80→    // This gives the embedding scorer a clean version even when dictionary repair misses.\n    81→    if (line.index <= 5 && OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text)) {\n    82→      const blindRepaired = applyBlindOcrRepair(singleText);\n    83→      if (blindRepaired !== singleText && passesHardFilters(blindRepaired)) {\n    84→        const norm = blindRepaired.toLowerCase();\n    85→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n    86→          seen.add(norm);\n    87→          candidates.push({ text: blindRepaired, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n    88→        }\n    89→      }\n    90→    }\n    91→```\n    92→\n    93→Note: `line.text` is checked for `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN` (the raw text), but `applyBlindOcrRepair` is applied to `singleText` (which already had dictionary-guided repair via `repairOcrText`). This way, blind repair fills in what dictionary repair missed.\n    94→\n    95→The `line.index <= 5` guard limits blind repair to the title region (first 5 lines), where positional evidence is strong enough to justify speculative substitution.\n    96→\n    97→## Verification\n    98→\n    99→1. Run `npx tsx tools/title-loop/eval_only.py` (or equivalent eval command) and check that the 5 Pattern 1 cases improve:\n   100→   - Braised Cod with White Wine\n   101→   - Drożdże Sernik\n   102→   - Piernik z Śliwkami\n   103→   - Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip\n   104→   - Żurek Krakowski\n   105→2. Verify no regressions on existing passing test cases\n   106→3. Verify that `normalizeOcrTitle` produces identical output after the refactor (it delegates to the same logic)\n   107→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Pn2J9YHaerVj5dEWKNBP49","session_id":"c37a3300-1904-44e6-bf34-65ba8b38fada","uuid":"42bbd18e-0e5d-455b-bdef-bc869bd3333f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CJNgqwp2MmJ2fDNuXDNUXy","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Task 02: Protect multi-line title joins from dedup when suffix is food-related\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Modify the dedup filter to keep multi-line join candidates when their suffix over the shorter prefix contains food-related words, preventing truncation of titles like \"LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES\" to \"LEMON HERB ROASTED\".\n     6→\n     7→## Files to modify\n     8→\n     9→- `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n    10→\n    11→## Changes\n    12→\n    13→### Modify the dedup filter (~lines 1376-1386)\n    14→\n    15→The current dedup filter at line 1376 removes longer candidates when a shorter substring exists. This incorrectly removes multi-line joins where the continuation word is a food term (e.g., \"VEGETABLES\"). Add a protection check for multi-line joins whose suffix contains food-related words.\n    16→\n    17→Current code:\n    18→```typescript\n    19→selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n    20→  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n    21→  // Protect compound titles — these use explicit separators and the full form is intentional\n    22→  if (/ [+:&] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n    23→  return !selected.some(\n    24→    (b) =>\n    25→      b !== a &&\n    26→      aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n    27→      b.text.length < a.text.length\n    28→  );\n    29→});\n    30→```\n    31→\n    32→New code:\n    33→```typescript\n    34→selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n    35→  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n    36→  // Protect compound titles — these use explicit separators and the full form is intentional\n    37→  if (/ [+:&] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n    38→  return !selected.some((b) => {\n    39→    if (b === a) return false;\n    40→    if (b.text.length >= a.text.length) return false;\n    41→    if (!aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase())) return false;\n    42→\n    43→    // Protect multi-line joins whose suffix over the shorter candidate is food-related.\n    44→    // E.g., \"LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES\" (2-line) vs \"LEMON HERB ROASTED\" (single):\n    45→    // \"VEGETABLES\" is in CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS, so keep the longer form.\n    46→    if ((a.origin === \"2-line\" || a.origin === \"3-line\") &&\n    47→        aLower.startsWith(b.text.toLowerCase() + \" \")) {\n    48→      const suffix = a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim();\n    49→      const suffixNorm = stripDiacritics(suffix.toLowerCase());\n    50→      if (CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS.has(suffixNorm) ||\n    51→          FOOD_DICTIONARY.has(suffixNorm) ||\n    52→          suffix.split(/\\s+/).some(w => FOOD_DICTIONARY.has(w.toLowerCase()))) {\n    53→        return false; // Don't remove `a` — its suffix is food-related\n    54→      }\n    55→    }\n    56→\n    57→    return true;\n    58→  });\n    59→});\n    60→```\n    61→\n    62→Key details:\n    63→- Only protects candidates with origin `\"2-line\"` or `\"3-line\"` (multi-line joins), not single-line candidates that happen to be longer\n    64→- Only fires when `a` starts with `b`'s text (prefix relationship), not arbitrary substring\n    65→- Checks the suffix against both `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` (e.g., \"vegetables\", \"soups\") and `FOOD_DICTIONARY` (broader food terms)\n    66→- Falls through to word-level check (`suffix.split(...).some(...)`) for multi-word suffixes\n    67→- `stripDiacritics` is already available in the file (used elsewhere for section label matching)\n    68→\n    69→Note the comment at line 1372 says \"DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC\". This change is safe because it only *adds* a protection for multi-line joins — the default behavior (shorter wins) is unchanged for all other cases. The existing protection for compound titles (`/ [+:&] /`) is also preserved.\n    70→\n    71→## Verification\n    72→\n    73→1. Run eval and check that the Pattern 3 case improves:\n    74→   - Lemon Herb Roasted Vegetables → should now extract the full title instead of truncating to \"LEMON HERB ROASTED\"\n    75→2. Verify no regressions, especially:\n    76→   - \"Pierogi Ruskie\" should still win over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\" (this is a substring, not a prefix-with-food-suffix case)\n    77→   - Other existing dedup behavior is preserved\n    78→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Pn2J9YHaerVj5dEWKNBP49","session_id":"c37a3300-1904-44e6-bf34-65ba8b38fada","uuid":"4621f417-b353-4160-9be2-7a37fae9d77c"}
