{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019Qr9GCBeoUL8HoJYpSjXZ6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Task 04: Extend spillover detection and scope corroboration to post-spillover region\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Lower the cooking-instruction prologue threshold in `findBurstEnd` from 5 to 3, and add a `startLine` parameter to `passesCorroboration` so the multi-title guard checks vocabulary only against the post-spillover region.\n     6→\n     7→## Files to modify\n     8→\n     9→- `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n    10→\n    11→## Changes\n    12→\n    13→### 1. Lower cooking-instruction threshold in `findBurstEnd` (line 484)\n    14→\n    15→In `findBurstEnd`, the cooking-instruction prologue skip currently requires 5+ consecutive instruction-like lines. Lower to 3 to catch shorter spillover blocks from previous recipes.\n    16→\n    17→Change line 484:\n    18→```typescript\n    19→// Before:\n    20→    if (j >= 5) {\n    21→// After:\n    22→    if (j >= 3) {\n    23→```\n    24→\n    25→Context (lines 477-487):\n    26→```typescript\n    27→  // Skip long instruction-like prologues: if 3+ consecutive lines look like cooking instructions,\n    28→  // skip them to find the actual title region.\n    29→  if (i === 0) {\n    30→    let j = 0;\n    31→    while (j < lines.length && looksLikeCookingInstruction(lines[j].text)) {\n    32→      j++;\n    33→    }\n    34→    if (j >= 3) {  // was: j >= 5\n    35→      i = j;\n    36→    }\n    37→  }\n    38→```\n    39→\n    40→Also update the comment on line 477 from \"5+ consecutive lines\" to \"3+ consecutive lines\".\n    41→\n    42→This is safe because iteration 26 improved `findBurstEnd`'s post-skip logic to look for structural markers (blank lines, separators, ALL_CAPS headings) before resuming — so even if we skip slightly more aggressively, the skip terminates at the first structural signal.\n    43→\n    44→### 2. Add `startLine` parameter to `passesCorroboration` (lines 243-268)\n    45→\n    46→Add an optional `startLine` parameter so corroboration can be scoped to only the post-spillover region of the document. This prevents spillover content from providing false vocabulary support for a foreign recipe title.\n    47→\n    48→Change the function signature and loop:\n    49→\n    50→```typescript\n    51→function passesCorroboration(\n    52→  text: string,\n    53→  position: number,\n    54→  allLines: string[],\n    55→  startLine: number = 0  // Only check corroboration against lines from this index onward\n    56→): boolean {\n    57→  const contentWords = extractContentWords(text);\n    58→\n    59→  if (contentWords.length === 0) {\n    60→    return true; // No checkable words — pass through\n    61→  }\n    62→\n    63→  let corroboratedCount = 0;\n    64→  for (const word of contentWords) {\n    65→    for (let i = startLine; i < allLines.length; i++) {  // was: i = 0\n    66→      if (i === position) continue;\n    67→      if (allLines[i].toUpperCase().includes(word)) {\n    68→        corroboratedCount++;\n    69→        break;\n    70→      }\n    71→    }\n    72→  }\n    73→\n    74→  const score = corroboratedCount / contentWords.length;\n    75→  const threshold = contentWords.length <= 3 ? 1.0 : 0.67;\n    76→  return score >= threshold;\n    77→}\n    78→```\n    79→\n    80→### 3. Pass `burstEnd` to corroboration in the multi-title guard (~lines 1397-1426)\n    81→\n    82→In the multi-title guard where `passesCorroboration` is called (line 1402-1404), pass the burst end position so vocabulary from spillover doesn't count as corroboration.\n    83→\n    84→To do this, `burstEnd` must be available in the scoring/filtering section. Currently `findBurstEnd` is called inside `buildCandidates` (line 549) and its result is local. Two approaches:\n    85→\n    86→**Option A (preferred):** Compute `burstEnd` from `buildCandidates`' return or recalculate it. Since `buildCandidates` already calls `findBurstEnd`, the simplest approach is to return `burstEnd` alongside the candidates. Modify `buildCandidates` to return `{ candidates, burstEnd }`:\n    87→\n    88→Change the return type/value of `buildCandidates`:\n    89→```typescript\n    90→function buildCandidates(\n    91→  lines: Array<string>\n    92→): { candidates: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }>; burstEnd: number } {\n    93→  // ... existing code ...\n    94→  const burstEnd = findBurstEnd(nonEmptyLines);\n    95→  // ... rest of function ...\n    96→  return { candidates, burstEnd: burstEnd > 0 ? nonEmptyLines[burstEnd - 1]?.index ?? 0 : 0 };\n    97→}\n    98→```\n    99→\n   100→Note: `burstEnd` from `findBurstEnd` is an index into `nonEmptyLines`, but we need it as a line index into the original `lines` array. Convert using `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd - 1]?.index ?? 0` (the original line index of the last skipped non-empty line), or `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? 0` (the first non-skipped line). Use the latter for the corroboration start line.\n   101→\n   102→Update the call site (in the main `extractTitle` function) to destructure:\n   103→```typescript\n   104→const { candidates, burstEnd } = buildCandidates(lines);\n   105→```\n   106→\n   107→Then in the multi-title guard (line 1402-1404), pass `burstEnd`:\n   108→```typescript\n   109→const corroboratedCaps = allCapsSelected.filter((cap) =>\n   110→  passesCorroboration(cap.text, cap.position, lines, burstEnd)\n   111→);\n   112→```\n   113→\n   114→**Option B (simpler):** Recompute `findBurstEnd` in the main function. This duplicates work but avoids changing `buildCandidates`' return type. Less clean but lower risk of breaking other call sites.\n   115→\n   116→Choose Option A unless the return type change causes issues at other call sites.\n   117→\n   118→## Verification\n   119→\n   120→1. Run eval and check that the 2 Pattern 4 cases improve:\n   121→   - Mushroom Risotto → should no longer