{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_011fnUvvNp84N8Kzee86wUTT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the key issue. `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` for mixed-case:\n```\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, oneLetter)\n.replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, oneLetter)\n.replace(/¡/g, \"i\")\n.replace(/€/g, \"e\")\n```\n\nIt ONLY handles:\n- `1` → `i`/`l` (between lowercase letters)\n- `¡` → `i`\n- `€` → `e`\n\nIt does NOT handle:\n\n\n- `0` → `o` (only handled in ALL_CAPS branch)\n- `4` → `a` (only handled in ALL_CAPS branch)  \n- `5` → `s` (only handled in ALL_CAPS branch)\n\nAnd for the `1` replacement, it requires lowercase context (`(?<=[a-zà-ż])1` or `1(?=[a-zà-ż])`). So:\n- `Bra1sed` → `1` is between `a` (lower) and `s` (lower) → matches → `Braised` ✓\n- `w1th` → `1` is between lowercase letters too, so it should match as well.\n- `Wh1te` → `1` is between `h` (lower) and `t` (lower) → matches → `White` ✓\n- `W1ne` → `1` is between `W` (upper) and `n` (lower) → only `1(?=[a-zà-ż])` matches → `Wine` ✓\n\nSo the `1→i` substitutions should all work, meaning \"Braised Cod with White Wine\" should be valid. But wait, I'm realizing the issue now — the lookbehind pattern only matches when there's a lowercase letter before the `1`, so `W1ne` wouldn't actually match the first pattern since `W` is uppercase.\n\nBut the lookahead pattern `1(?=[a-zà-ż])` does match because `n` is lowercase, so `W1ne` still becomes `Wine`. Same logic applies to `D1p` — the lookahead catches it even though `D` is uppercase. So the blind repair should work and the variants should be generated since the position and OCR pattern conditions are met. Let me trace through the actual flow to see where things break down.\n\nThe issue is that dictionary repair runs first on the single text, then blind repair runs on whatever's left. If dictionary repair already fixed some `1`s to valid words, the blind repair might not find any artifacts to work with. And I need to check whether \"Braised\" is actually in the food dictionary to understand if that's where the repair happens. food dictionary? Let me check... The food dictionary likely contains cooking terms. \"braised\" might be there.\n\nIf `repairOcrWord(\"Bra1sed\")` → \"Braised\", then `repairOcrText(\"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\")` → \"Braised Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\" (only \"Bra1sed\" was in dictionary). Then `singleText` = \"Braised Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\". This passes `passesHardFilters`? Maybe not if `isLikelyGarbled` triggers on digits in words.\n\nActually wait — `passesHardFilters` calls `isLikelyGarbled`. The garbled detection checks vowel ratios, internal caps, isolated short words, pipes, and Cyrillic characters, but it might not specifically flag embedded digits. If the text clears the hard filters despite those `1` characters, then both the partially-repaired and fully-repaired versions get added as candidates. But the result came back empty, which means either nothing passed the hard filters, the scores were too low, or the `titleAbsent` guard filtered everything out. I think I need to look at the actual input to understand what's happening — if most lines are corrupted, the embedding scorer probably can't differentiate between candidates effectively.\n\nNow I'm ready to consolidate what I've learned. The core problems are the incomplete OCR repair mappings missing `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s`, the failure to recover corrupted titles with good fallbacks, the tendency for clean titles to lose to garbage tokens, and the erratic casing and special character handling that breaks detection.\n\nLooking deeper at why Patterns 1 & 2 fail: the blind OCR repair generates variants, but the logic doesn't reliably surface the best candidate—either the repaired text fails the hard filters, the variants don't score high enough, or the threshold logic picks the wrong option. So if dictionary repair already fixes all the corrupted characters like the `1`s, then the blind repair variants won't find anything to fix and returns empty. That means `singleText` becomes clean (\"Braised Cod with White Wine\") and should pass the hard filters as the original candidate—unless dictionary repair only partially fixes it, leaving some artifacts that still block it.\n\nThe issue is that words like \"w1th\" probably won't get repaired because \"with\" isn't a food dictionary word, so it stays corrupted. That means the text still contains digits that might trigger the garbled detection, so I need to check what `isLikelyGarbled` actually looks for.\n\nBut stepping back, the feedback makes the real problem clear: the corrupted first line gets rejected and no fallback strategy saves it. The fix needs better OCR repair for mixed-case substitutions like `0→o`, a stronger positional bias toward first-line candidates, better handling of metadata appearing before titles, and acknowledgment that some documents genuinely don't have extractable titles. Let me write up the improvement plan now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3108,"cache_read_input_tokens":52172,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3108},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c37a3300-1904-44e6-bf34-65ba8b38fada","uuid":"255528ea-b53a-40ea-a612-ac8e54880423"}
