{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013DhADYuCSdJDaezYfiC6mz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the key issue with the Ogórkowa Zupa case:\n\nThe pipe-separated metadata line `Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | PRZYGOTOWANIE 15 MIN | GOTOWANIE 20 MIN`:\n1. It has `\" | \"` which makes `passesHardFilters` reject it at line 393 (`if (text.includes(\" | \")) return false`)\n2. It also matches several METADATA_PATTERNS: `DLA\\s+\\d` and `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b`\n\nSo the metadata line is correctly filtered out. \n\nThen `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` is the next non-empty line. It should pass hard filters (ALL_CAPS, 2 words, no section label), but the result is empty. The first-after-preamble bonus should trigger since the metadata line gets filtered out, making `allPrecedingFiltered` true, which means the title should receive the bonus and rank higher.\n\nBut what if `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` never becomes a candidate in the first place? Tracing through `buildCandidates`, the metadata line isn't short or garbled, so `burstEnd = 0` and it gets included in the merged lines. When processing line 0, the metadata text fails the hard filters check because of the pipe character, so it gets filtered out.\n\nThen when I reach `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` on the next iteration, I'm checking whether it passes all the filters — it has acceptable length, isn't an ingredient or number-prefixed, isn't metadata, isn't garbled, and doesn't contain pipes. The real question is whether it's being classified as a section label, but `ogorkowa zupa` shouldn't match anything in the section labels list, so it should pass through as a valid candidate.\n\nBut if it's passing the hard filters and getting added as a candidate, why is the final result empty? The embedding score must be the culprit — MiniLM might struggle with Polish text in all caps, giving it a very low or even negative raw score that doesn't recover even with the all-caps bonus applied.\n\nLet me trace through the scoring: if the raw score is around -0.15, after applying position, all-caps, structural, and preamble bonuses, it should land around 0.15, which clears the 0.08 threshold. Unless the `titleAbsent` guard is blocking it — I need to check what that function actually does to see if it's filtering out pages where the first few lines are all ingredients, instructions, or prose. I keep coming back to the same issue — maybe the problem is simpler than I'm making it. Let me look at the actual file structure again. The metadata might be split across multiple lines, or there could be something unexpected before it that's throwing off the parsing. Without seeing the exact content, I should just acknowledge this needs investigation and move forward with drafting the improvement plan based on what I know about the nine failures.\n\nLooking at the proposed changes, the first priority is completing the mixed-case OCR repair by adding context-aware substitutions for the digits `0`, `4`, and `5` that are currently missing. The second change involves expanding the Polish cooking verb filter to catch more instruction patterns that are currently being misidentified as body text.\n\nFor the third change, I need to improve garbled token detection to catch tokens like `Xxyyzz` that look syntactically normal but are actually nonsensical — the current check only flags mixed-case transitions, so I should add a heuristic that catches tokens with excessive consonant clusters or other structural anomalies that indicate corruption. — `Xxyyzz` has vowels? X-x-y-y-z-z. The vowels check: `y` is a vowel → 2/6 = 33% vowel ratio. That passes the 10%-85% check. Hmm.\n\nActually, `Xxyyzz` starts with uppercase but has `[a-z][A-Z]` transition? No: `X-x-y-y-z-z`. It's `Xx...` — uppercase X then lowercase x. That's `[A-Z][a-z]` which is normal title case. Then no more uppercase. So the `[a-z][A-Z]` single-word check doesn't fire.\n\nBut the multi-word garbled check looks for short lowercase words that aren't common. In \"Xxyyzz salt and pepper\", the words `salt`, `and`, `pepper` all start lowercase with length ≥3, so they don't trigger the garbled fragment detection. And `Xxyyzz` itself starts uppercase, so it doesn't match either. The filter completely misses this as garbage because `Xxyyzz` appears plausible on its own.\n\nNow I'm checking if corroboration would catch it. , has >4 characters, and contains no vowels other than `y` — that would catch the repeated consonant pattern. But `Xxyyzz` actually has two y's, which are vowels in English, so that heuristic breaks down. The real problem is that the embedding gets pulled toward the legitimate food words in the string, drowning out the nonsense prefix. I should instead validate that the first word of a multi-word candidate is actually recognizable — if the leading word fails a dictionary check, the whole thing should be rejected.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The subagent's report shows the actual text is `XxYyZz salt and pepper`, not `Xxyyzz`. That alternating case pattern with transitions like `x→Y` and `y→Z` is a strong signal of garbled text, so I should strengthen the garbled word detection to catch those mixed-case transitions specifically.\n\nThe issue is that the current check at line 302 only flags single-word candidates with lowercase-to-uppercase transitions, but `XxYyZz` is part of a multi-word candidate. For multi-word cases, the garbled detection at lines 318-333 skips words starting with uppercase, so `XxYyZz` gets missed entirely. I need to extend that multi-word garbled check to also catch words with those internal case transitions, not just single-word ones.\n\nNow for the Ogórkowa Zupa case—the metadata line with pipes might be getting filtered out by `passesHardFilters`, but `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` should still be a candidate. I'm wondering if the real issue is that `findBurstEnd` is classifying the entire opening section as a body-content prologue, and the metadata line isn't triggering any of the expected instruction or continuation patterns that would let the detector move past it.\n\nLet me trace through this differently—maybe the problem lies in how `buildCandidates` processes the metadata line's position in the `nonEmptyLines` array, since it's at the original index 0 but gets mapped differently when empty lines are filtered out. The blind repair variants would still contain the pipe character, so they'd fail the hard filters too. Then I'm checking `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` as the next candidate — after repair it stays the same, and it should pass the hard filters since it's clean text without artifacts or problematic characters. owa zupa`. It's a recipe name, not a section label, so that check should fail. The entry should qualify as a candidate—it's all caps with bonuses from capitalization, structure, and position that could push it over the threshold. The real question is whether the MiniLM model penalizes Polish words heavily enough to tank the raw score, or if other candidates score higher and set a stricter threshold.\n\nThe core issue is that the embedding model is English-focused and struggles with Polish all-caps text. My approach is to boost the positional bonus when we see all-caps text appearing right after metadata or section headers, letting structural signals override weak embedding scores. Now I'll map out the specific fixes needed in the code.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1092,"cache_read_input_tokens":70209,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1092},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c37a3300-1904-44e6-bf34-65ba8b38fada","uuid":"083df310-a5e0-4dda-9f7a-cbd9dbbec0a0"}
